{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BRsEV86HbhssyN9TNJz4vP","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The RabbitMQ Prometheus plugin doesn't expose a `rabbitmq_up` metric. The `rabbitmq_up` metric is generated by Prometheus itself as a standard target health metric. When Prometheus can successfully scrape a target, it sets `up{job=\"rabbitmq\", instance=\"...\"}` to 1.\n\nWait, `up` is the metric name for this, not `rabbitmq_up`. The `rabbitmq_up` metric would only exist if:\n1. Prometheus generates a metric called `rabbitmq_up` (it doesn't - it uses `up` for all jobs)\n2. The RabbitMQ exporter generates it (the official RabbitMQ Prometheus plugin doesn't seem to)\n3. There's a recording rule that creates it\n\nLooking at the RabbitMQ Prometheus plugin documentation, `rabbitmq_up` is actually exposed by the older `rabbitmq_prometheus` plugin, which is different from the native Prometheus plugin. In newer RabbitMQ versions (3.8+), the native Prometheus support should be available, but I need to verify whether `rabbitmq_up` is actually among the exposed metrics or if I should be using a different metric name.\n\nSince the task mentions that querying `rabbitmq_up` returns 3 samples, maybe the metric does exist on the RabbitMQ metrics endpoint, or perhaps I need to create a recording rule for it. Let me check what metrics are actually available from the RabbitMQ endpoint.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":844,"cache_read_input_tokens":39131,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":844},"output_tokens":40,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cefcb7a8-c1a0-4ae7-9c71-6320dc475973","uuid":"0bf02c15-1563-4cfd-a235-f284f0162684","request_id":"req_011CcbqzrVaVYhbvZxcn9